{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}} {{Use British English|date=January 2017}} [[File:"All felled, felled, are all felled" - geograph.org.uk - 955436.jpg|thumb|‘All felled, felled, are all felled’ — photograph of felled [[Populus|poplar]] trees with a line from the poem ‘Binsey Poplars’.]] [[File:GerardManleyHopkins.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Gerard Manley Hopkins]], author of ‘Binsey Poplars’.]]
‘Binsey Poplars’ is a poem by [[Gerard Manley Hopkins]] (1844–1889), written in 1879.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bartleby.com/122/19.html | title=19, Binsey Poplars | work=Gerard Manley Hopkins (1844–89): Poems | publisher=[[Bartleby.com]] | date=2 May 2013 | accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.sparknotes.com/poetry/hopkins/section6.rhtml |title="Binsey Poplars" (1879) | work=Hopkins's Poetry | publisher=[[SparkNotes]]| accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> The poem was inspired by the felling of a row of [[Populus|poplar]] trees near the village of [[Binsey, Oxfordshire|Binsey]], northwest of [[Oxford]], [[England]], and overlooking [[Port Meadow]] on the bank of the [[River Thames]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.igreens.org.uk/binsey_poplars.htm | title=The Binsey Poplars | website=iGreens.org.uk | first=Jim | last=Thornton | date=12 December 2002 | accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> The replacements for these trees, running from Binsey north to [[Godstow]], lasted until 2004, when replanting began again.<ref>{{Cite book | first=Leight | last=Hatts |title=The Thames Path | year=2005 | publisher=[[Cicerone Press]] |isbn=978-1-85284-436-3 }}</ref>
The [[Bodleian Library]] of [[Oxford University]] holds a draft manuscript of the poem, handwritten by Hopkins, acquired in 2013.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/bodley/news/binsey-poplars | title=Bodleian acquires manuscript of Hopkins poem 'Binsey Poplars' | publisher=[[Bodleian Library]], [[Oxford University]] | date=2 May 2013 | accessdate=2 February 2014 }}</ref>
==The poem== The text of the poem is as follows:<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.poetryfoundation.org/poem/173655 |title=Binsey Poplars by Gerard Manley Hopkins | work=Poem | publisher=[[Poetry Foundation]] | accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.poemhunter.com/poem/binsey-poplars/ | title=Binsey Poplars | website=poemhunter.com | accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref>
{{quote|<poem>My [[aspen]]s dear, whose airy cages quelled, Quelled or quenched in leaves the leaping sun, All felled, felled, are all felled; Of a fresh and following folded rank Not spared, not one That dandled a sandalled Shadow that swam or sank On meadow and river and wind-wandering weed-winding bank. &nbsp; O if we but knew what we do When we delve or hew— Hack and rack the growing green! Since country is so tender To touch, her being so slender, That, like this sleek and seeing ball But a prick will make no eye at all, Where we, even where we mean To mend her we end her, When we hew or delve: After-comers cannot guess the beauty been. Ten or twelve, only ten or twelve Strokes of havoc unselve The sweet especial scene, Rural scene, a rural scene, Sweet especial rural scene.</poem>}}
==See also== * [[Poplar Walk]], [[Christ Church Meadow]]
