{{EngvarB|date=July 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}} {{Infobox Airliner accident| name=[[Cameroon Airlines]] Flight 786| Date=30 August 1984 | Type=Fire (during taxi)| occurrence_type=Accident| image=Boeing 737-219-Adv AN0988555.jpg| caption=A Boeing 737-200 similar to the accident aircraft| Site=[[Douala Airport]], [[Cameroon]]| Fatalities=2| Injuries=Unknown | Aircraft Type=[[Boeing 737|Boeing 737-2H7C]]| Operator=[[Cameroon Airlines]] | Tail Number=TJ-CBD| Passengers=109| Crew=7 | Survivors = 114 | }}
'''Cameroon Airlines Flight 786''' was a [[Boeing 737|Boeing 737-2H7C]], registration TJ-CBD, operating as a scheduled domestic passenger flight from [[Douala Airport]], [[Cameroon]] ([[ICAO]]: FKKD), to [[Garoua]] via [[Yaoundé]]. On 30 August 1984, as the aircraft was taxiing out for takeoff with 109 passengers and a crew of 7 on board, its number two engine suffered an [[Turbine engine failure#Contained versus uncontained failures|uncontained compressor failure]], which started a fire. All occupants were able to evacuate the aircraft, but two passengers died due to fire outside the cabin.<ref name=caa/> The aircraft burned to the ground and was declared a total loss.<ref name=asn>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19840830-0|title=ASN accident record|publisher=ASN|accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref>
==Accident sequence== As the aircraft was taxiing out in preparation for takeoff, a high-pressure compressor disk in the number two (right side) [[Pratt & Whitney JT8D|Pratt & Whitney JT8D-15]] engine failed and disintegrated, with fragments damaging the right wing and perforating the fuel tank.<ref name=caa/> The fuel began leaking from the ruptured tank onto the ground below the aircraft, and a fire was ignited. All occupants were able to evacuate the aircraft, but two passengers died due to the fire outside.<ref name=caa>{{cite web|url=http://www.fire.tc.faa.gov/pdf/CAPAP2002_4.PDF|title=A Benefit Analysis for Cabin Water Spray Systems and Enhanced Fuselage Burnthrough Protection|publisher=CAA (UK)|accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref> The plane was completely destroyed.<ref name=asn/>
==Aftermath== According to Cameroon Airline's Chief Pilot (ret.) Jean Louis Angounou, interviewed in May 2009 on ''Le Jour Quotidien'', the exact cause of the accident has never been determined because "in Cameroon, some inquiries begin but never come to an end."<ref name=lejour>{{cite news|url=http://www.lejourquotidien.info/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=4558&Itemid=60|language=French|title=Jean Louis Angounou : Le président Ahidjo m'a dit ...|publisher=Le Jour Quotidien, Cameroon|date=25 May 2009}}</ref>
