{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}
{{Use British English|date=March 2014}}
'''HMS ''Friday''''' is an [[urban myth]] concerning a disastrous attempt by the [[Royal Navy]] to dispel the [[Friday#Folklore|superstition against sailing on a Friday]]. While widely circulated, the story is in fact untrue;<ref>{{cite web|title=The Top 10 Superstitions About Boating|url=http://www.popyachts.com/Page/Site-Post-List/111/The-Top-10-Superstitions-About-Boating.html | accessdate = 2014-08-14}}</ref> moreover, there was never even a ship named HMS ''Friday''.<ref>Eyers, Jonathan (2011). ''Don't Shoot the Albatross!: Nautical Myths and Superstitions''. A&C Black, London, UK. {{ISBN|978-1-4081-3131-2}}.</ref>

The details of the story vary, but it usually follows this form:
<blockquote>Sometime in the 19th century, the Royal Navy attempted to finally dispel the old superstition among sailors that beginning a voyage on a Friday was certain to bring bad luck. To demonstrate the falseness of this belief, they decided to commission a ship named HMS ''Friday''. Her keel was laid on a Friday, she was launched on a Friday, and she set sail on her [[maiden voyage]] on [[Friday the 13th]], under the command of a Captain James Friday. She was never seen or heard from again.</blockquote>

This story, in numerous variations, is frequently recounted, often as fact.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://geekswithblogs.net/mtreadwell/archive/2004/04/16/3995.aspx |title=Nautical Folklore: Superstition of Friday |accessdate=2008-09-29}}</ref><ref name=lennox>{{Cite book |last=Lennox |first=Doug |title=Now You Know: The Book of Answers |page=110 |publisher=Dundurn Press Ltd. |year=2003 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ea_2cNCGmfIC&pg=PA109-IA1&dq=hms+friday |isbn=1-55002-461-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://urbanlegends.about.com/cs/historical/a/friday_the_13th_3.htm |title=Why Friday the 13th Is Unlucky |publisher=about.com |accessdate=2008-09-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.infoplease.com/spot/friday13th.html |title=Friday the 13th |publisher=Infoplease |accessdate=2008-09-29}}</ref><ref name=vigor>{{Cite book |last=Vigor |first=John |title=The Practical Encyclopedia of Boating |publisher=McGraw-Hill Professional |year=2004 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VLg6Lx5yRP0C&pg=RA1-PA258&lpg=RA1-PA258&dq=hms+friday |isbn=0-07-137885-5}}</ref> It also appeared as a small "filler" item in the magazine "Reader's Digest", its format giving the impression of having been historically researched.{{citation needed|date=October 2018}}

In fact, there has never been any Royal Navy ship of that name.<ref name=vigor/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royalnavalmuseum.org/new_whatsnew.htm |title=RNM News, 13th July 2007: No truth in 'HMS Friday' story |publisher=Royal Naval Museum |accessdate=2008-09-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/hampshire/6896203.stm |title=Naval Friday 13th myth unfounded |publisher=BBC News Online |accessdate=2008-09-29 |date=2007-07-12}}</ref> It is unclear where the story originated; however, it seems to have gained in popularity after its recounting by comedian [[Dave Allen (comedian)|Dave Allen]] on his [[BBC]] television show ''Dave Allen at Large'', Series 1, Episode 2, first broadcast 4 February 1971.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://trancefixed.wordpress.com/2006/08/12/myth-of-the-day-01/ |title=Myth of the Day 01 - HMS Friday |publisher=Trancefixed |accessdate=2008-09-29}}</ref>

