{{Husayn}} A '''Tabuik''' is the local manifestation of the [[Remembrance of Muharram]] among the [[Minangkabau people|Minangkabau]] people in the coastal regions of [[West Sumatra]], [[Indonesia]], particularly in the city of [[Pariaman]].
==History== [[File:Tabuik festival.jpg|left|thumb|175px|''Tabuik'' being lowered into the sea in Pariaman]] A "''tabuik''" also refers to the towering funeral [[bier]]s carried around during the remembrance procession, and is similar in form to several of the [[Indigenous peoples of North America|indigenous cultures]]' [[totem]]s found in the [[Western culture|old world Western cultures]].
The practice of throwing a tabuik into the sea has taken place every year in Pariaman on the [[Day of Ashura|10th of Muharram]] since 1831.<ref name="jpost">{{cite news | last = Bachyul Jb | first = Syofiardi | title = 'Tabuik' festival: From a religious event to tourism | publisher = [[The Jakarta Post]] | date = 2006-03-01 | url = http://www.tmcnet.com/usubmit/2006/03/01/1422473.htm | accessdate = 2007-01-27 }}</ref> The practice was introduced to the region by the [[Shi'ite Muslim]] ''[[sepoy]]'' troops from [[India]] who were stationed—and later settled—there during the [[British Raj]].<ref name="jpost" />
==The events== [[Image:Tabuik Pariaman.jpg|rt|upright|thumb|200px|A tabuik monument in the center of [[Pariaman]], [[Indonesia]] ]] The festival includes [[Historical reenactment|reenactment]]s of the [[Battle of Karbala]], and the playing of [[tassa]] and [[dhol]] drums. Although originally a Shi'a festival, nowadays most inhabitants of Pariaman and other southeastern Asia areas hold similar festivals which are even celebrated by non-Muslims.
==The remembrance bier== The remembrance is referred to as ''Tabut'' or ''[[Tabot]]'' in [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]]. (Tabut is the name given in the [[Quran]] for The [[Ark of the Covenant]].) In preparation for the ceremony, one or more tabuiks are made from [[bamboo]], [[rattan]], and paper. During the week of Tabuik, activities include kite races, traditional plays, and dance expositions (such as the ''[[Tari Piring]]''). The memorial draws a large crowd including dignitaries such as the provincial governor. Visitors and celebrants can observe the tabuik in the morning before it is slowly taken to the beach in a procession. At noon the tabuik is thrown into the sea. Afterwards, many people go swimming creating 'memories' of the tabuik to keep.
==See also== * [[Culture of Indonesia]] * [[Islam in Indonesia]] * [[Shi'a Islam in Indonesia]] * [[Hosay]]
